I&#39;m glad I could help :)

I didn&#39;t put much thought into the &quot;design&quot; and I didn&#39;t try to implement
the tests (normally I would write one test, watch it not compile, make it
compile, watch it fail, make it pass, refactor or atleast review what I did,
see that it still passes, next test). So if you find that my code doesn&#39;t
make sense it&#39;s probably because it doesn&#39;t :). I just wanted to show the
aporoach.

And remeber there are many ways to skin a cat so if my way does not suit
your needs adopt someone elses.
About black-boxing/whiteboxing there are different levels of that. I think
unittests are generally on the whiter shade of the scale although some would
say my tests are too white; I hope those people post their aproach so that
you can compare and pick what works for you. My constant advice to myself is
&quot;if it&#39;s hard I&#39;m doing something wrong&quot;. Sometimes that leads me to change
my design, sometimes it leadds me to change the way I test. Experiment,
practice and look how others do it. I can recomend reading the TDD list
aswell, lots of good stuff posted there.

Good luck!
/Joakim Ohlrogge

